# **IRL Merch with NFTs + Second Astronaut Marketing Final Report**

# [proposal](https://snapshot.org/#/tomoondao.eth/proposal/0xd0b4c7f0bbdfbb730a7d83266a0e714462581fa8bea9a8f3a1b9c2feb3da3de8)

### **In a nutshell**

# Overall the project fulfilled its main objective of having attendance with zero stable coin cost, and it was revealed that a model with pre-sales is not sustainable considering shipping costs, taxes, and the number of necessary hours to fulfill the orders. Drop-shipping services are really low quality for complex artwork, but the overall impact was excellent, even considering the settle backs and political changes. The outcome proves the point that it is feasible to attend conferences, making money from them, but would need further development to become scalable.

### **Main Challenges**

# - The treasury multi-sig transaction took some time to go through

- The Spect form used had problems and people couldn't fill it out to get into the allowlist.

- The form used to get the wallets messed up the formating, and I needed to copy and paste individually.

- Credit cards are a big deal for irl sales

- Didn't have enough Merch on my hands

- Printing Services with poor quality or long waiting lists

- Domestic and international shipping that were not expected in the original scope**.** 

- Sell all day along is exhausting, and can make hard to create meaningful connections

- Some Drama with the ETH Rio producers

- The Market Making strategy had problems in the batch transactions

- The application for the Hedge and Market making strategy using the Binance Cloud service was rejected for the 1st time and I still have no concrete idea why.

- Opensea changed the policy for contracts with royalties reinforcement functions

- Opensea came back with the 2,5% fee for polygon NFTs

- There is a lot of resistance with talks that mention crypto or web3 on embassies 

- With the new agreement between BR and CN the main feedback was that it's not the best moment to talk, or pick a fight, about american VISAs for CN citizens in Brazil.

Get a good print, with a quality fabric for t-shirt is a real challenge. When it happens, it's expensive for small quantities. There is a profitable path by having really limited series of higher quality shirts, and a lot more average with 1 or 2 colors to print on demand and drop-ship. But it is still a lot of work to keep the pace of orders, take care of specific tax regulations on each country,  and make sure that everyone got their orders. After almost 1 month of the shipping I discovered, meeting one client at NFT BR (and then following up with everyone that didn't send me confirmation on the same region), that some orders (4) got stuck on customs and required an additional doc to be released. 1 person (that bought 2 pieces) asked me for a refund, and gave the NFTs back. For the second one, I printed 2 t-shirts (just in case that one of them was bad quality), and gave 1 + 1 NFT.
